    <item>
      <title>Editor Tools - Unity Game Engine</title>
      <link>https://www.adamormsby.com/projects/unity-tools/</link>
      <pubDate>Thu, 01 Aug 2013 00:00:00 -0500</pubDate>
      
      <guid>https://www.adamormsby.com/projects/unity-tools/</guid>
      <description>&lt;h2 id=&#34;about&#34;&gt;About&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;During my time as a Unity developer, I programmed some editor tools to make certain tasks in the editor a bit easier for designers and other developers.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Legacy 2 PBR&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/em&gt; - When Unity introduced their Physically-Based Rendering system (PBR), a lot of teams wanted to update their shaders to work with the new system. My tool did this automatically! Users could drop their shaders into a custom editor window and automatically see the nearest built-in PBR equivalent. (If they didn&amp;rsquo;t like that, they could also select an output shader themselves.) With the click of a button, new shaders would be created based on their mapping. This tool was for sale on the Unity Asset Store.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Easy Layers&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/em&gt; - This was a nifty tool that gave users quick and easy scripting access to Unity&amp;rsquo;s physical layer masking systems. This tool was for sale on the Unity Asset Store.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Random Obstacle Generator&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/em&gt; - I made a proprietary tool for the &lt;a href=&#34;https://www.adamormsby.com/projects/yetis-quest/&#34; &gt;&lt;!-- raw HTML omitted --&gt;Yeti’s Quest&lt;!-- raw HTML omitted --&gt;&lt;/a&gt; project that allowed our level designer to adjust the random obstacle generation values along the player&amp;rsquo;s running path. It saved a ton of time and relieved the burden of editing code files directly.&lt;/p&gt;
